'''Endogenous preferences''' are [[preference]]s that cannot be taken as given, but are affected by individual internal responses to the external [[State of affairs (sociology)|state of affairs]]. They are interdependent, in part determined by social institutions, marketed advertisement, and subject to learning (experience and observation) and habit formation (past-experience).

