{{lead too short|date=January 2017}} '''Stuart Pivar''' (born 1930) is a [[chemist]], [[art collector]] and [[author]] from Brooklyn, [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref> {{cite web |title=On the Origin of Form – Author |url=http://www.ontheoriginofform.com/authors.html |work=www.ontheoriginofform.com |accessdate=2011-09-18 }}</ref>
==New York art world== Pivar earned a [[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc]] in chemistry at [[Hofstra University]]. An inventor, he made a large fortune in plastics, founding Chem-Tainer industries in 1959. The business specialised in bulk-storage [[plastic container]]s. While remaining active in the [[plastics industry]], he became an independently wealthy investor and buyer on the art scene.<ref>Paul Alexander, ''Death and disaster: the rise of the Warhol empire and the race for Andy's millions'', Villard Books, 1994, p.14.</ref> Pivar soon met [[Andy Warhol]], becoming one of his closest longtime friends. With Warhol he would go on regular shopping trips to buy "masterpieces", which could be objects bought anywhere, from a high-end auction house to a fleamarket.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Alexander |first=Paul |date=27 January 1992 |title=What happened to Andy's Treasures? |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=gOMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=Stuart+Pivar&hl=en&ei=Ku2JTrqoGNHOswbE2fDgAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFIQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Stuart%20Pivar&f=false |journal=[[New York Magazine]] |volume= |issue= |page=28 }}</ref> After the artist's death, Pivar recalled that "Andy Warhol loved to buy art. We used to go shopping together for it for a few hours practically every day in the past couple of years."<ref>Russell W. Belk, ''Collecting in a consumer society'', Psychology Press, 1995, p.72</ref>
Pivar was a collector of 19th-century [[academic art]] at a time when it was unfashionable.<ref>''Art & antiques'', Volume 22, 1999, p.99</ref> A scholar of the work of the sculptor [[Antoine-Louis Barye]], he wrote "The Barye Bronzes: A Catalogue Raisonne" in 1974, a collation of critical commentary on all the sculptor's known works.<ref> {{cite book |last1=Day |first1=H.T. |last2=Sturges |first2=H. |year=1987 |title=Joslyn Art Museum, paintings & sculpture from the European & American collections |page=77 |publisher=[[University of Nebraska Press]] |isbn= }}</ref><ref> {{cite book |last= |first= |year=1996 |title=19th century European paintings, drawings and sculpture |publisher=[[Sotheby's]] |page=265 }}</ref>
Pivar wished to reintroduce traditional skills to the teaching of art, including human and animal anatomy. With Warhol, he helped to found the [[New York Academy of Art]] in 1979, becoming one of its board members. The academy opposed [[abstract art]] and promoted traditional skills. According to [[Eliot Goldfinger]], Pivar "strongly supported the acquisition of an anatomical collection of comparative skeletons, related artwork, anatomical models and charts, and the use of dissection as part of the curriculum."<ref>Eliot Goldfinger, ''Animal anatomy for artists: the elements of form'', Oxford University Press, 2004, p.ix.</ref> He donated over $1.2 million to the Academy during his involvement with it.<ref name = "conn"/>
He resigned from the Academy in 1994, complaining that he had been "lied to and outmaneuvered" by other senior figures at the institution. A report placed most of the blame on his "disruptive, angry and abusive" behavior for problems at the institution.<ref name = "conn"> {{Cite journal |last=Connolly |first=J. |date=8 April 1996 |title=How could it be that board members at the New York Academy of Art were too busy fighting with each other to notice that $175,000 was missing? |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NOECAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=%22Stuart+Pivar%22&hl=en&ei=U2d2TsOhNMHE0AGWgoG0DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEgQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22Stuart%20Pivar%22&f=false |journal=[[New York Magazine]] |volume= |issue= |page=24 }}</ref> Pivar attempted to sue the Academy for $50 million, claiming that he had been caused "emotional and mental distress" and that he had been ostracised for pointing out falsification of financial records and employment of illegal immigrants.<ref name=50mildolsuit>{{Cite journal |last= |first= |date=1 Dec 1997 |title=Stuart Pivar's New $50 million Suit |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOgCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&dq=Stuart+Pivar&hl=en&ei=ZfGJTsyOKoXUsgaD-7DhAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCwQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Stuart%20Pivar&f=false |journal=[[New York Magazine]] |volume= |issue= |page=25 }}</ref> The academy's spokesman said that the lawsuit was frivolous, and pointed to a previous lawsuit filed by Pivar, which had been thrown out, stating he expected the new one to suffer the same fate.<ref name=50mildolsuit />
==Biological theories== Beginning with his book ''Lifecode'' in 2004 Pivar has published novel claims about the evolution of species. He asserts that the body form of [[species]] are encoded not in [[DNA]] but in the patterned structure of a primordial [[germ plasm]].<ref>On the Origin of Form: Evolution by Self-Organization, Stuart Pivar, North Atlantic Books, 2009 {{ISBN|1-55643-886-9}}</ref><ref name=Macmenamin>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:CU2gyUDK2twJ:www.ilasol.org.il/ILASOL/uploads/files/ILASOLintroductionV6.pdf+stuart+pivar+evolution&hl=en&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgA0o56t0DdMsclymOItS6OIWzPV56kTS3wQLD-PR3oVeFoSq65ffq6ao3hpRCK2uIO_Xa2GIXgXb5FRAQtfEmXVnsEKZbjvoN4FK6Toiybb6Y2855TZQhmxR0tCF84NG0A9cFc&sig=AHIEtbRqUvyz5yqYuyyf9A9wINXZDT3ynQ ILAOL introduction by Mark Macmenamin]</ref> However, critics have stated that Pivar's proposed developmental sequences bear no resemblance to anything actually observed during embryological development.<ref name=Macmenamin /> [[Massimo Pigliucci]] says that Pivar's ideas constitute [[pseudoscience]]. On his blog [[Pharyngula (blog)|"Pharyngula"]], developmental biologist [[PZ Myers]] reviewed ''Lifecode'' and concluded that it was "a description of the development and evolution of balloon animals".<ref>{{Citation |last = Myers |first = PZ |author-link = PZ Myers |publication-date = July 17, 2007 |title = Lifecode: From egg to embryo by self-organization |type = blog |work = Pharyngula |publisher = ScienceBlogs |url = http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2007/07/lifecode_from_egg_to_embryo_by.php |accessdate = October 5, 2011 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070906043449/http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2007/07/lifecode_from_egg_to_embryo_by.php |archivedate = September 6, 2007 |df = }}</ref> In 2007 Pivar attempted to sue ''Seed Media'', whose [[ScienceBlogs]] hosted "Pharyngula", for describing him as "classic crackpot",<ref>{{Citation |last = Myers |first = PZ |author-link = PZ Myers |publication-date = July 12, 2007 |title = Lifecode |type = blog |work = Pharyngula |publisher = ScienceBlogs |url = http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2007/07/lifecode.php |accessdate = October 5, 2011 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070907142321/http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2007/07/lifecode.php |archivedate = September 7, 2007 |df = }}</ref> but the case was withdrawn after ten days.<ref> {{cite book |last1=Delta |first1=George B. |last2=Matsuura |first2=Jeffrey H. |year=2009 |title=Law of the Internet, Volume 1, 2009 supplement |pages=11–12 |publisher=Aspen Publishers |isbn= }}</ref><ref>Massimo Pigliucci, ''Nonsense on stilts: how to tell science from bunk'', 2010, p. 101</ref><ref> {{Citation | last= Keim | first= Brandon | publication-date= August 20, 2007 | title= Pseudoscience not Selling? Just Sue a Science Blogger for Libel | work= Wired Science | publisher= Condé Nast Digital | url= https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2007/08/pseudoscience-n/ | accessdate= October 5, 2011 }}</ref> On July 5, 2016 a scientific paper titled ''The Origin of the Vertebrate Body Plan in the Geometric Patterns in the Embryonic Blastula'' was published in the peer-reviewed journal ''Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology'' identifying Stuart Pivar as the principal investigator. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Edelman|first1=David B. |last2=McMenamin|first2=Mark |last3=Sheesley|first3=Peter |last4=Pivar|first4=Stuart |title=Origin of the vertebrate body plan via mechanically biased conservation of regular geometrical patterns in the structure of the blastula |journal=Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology |date=July 5, 2016 |doi=10.1016/j.pbiomolbio.2016.06.007 |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0079610716300542}} </ref>
==Publications== *{{cite journal |last1=Edelman|first1=D.B. |last2=McMenamin|first2=M. |last3=Sheesley|first3=P. |last4=Pivar|first4=S. |year=2016 |title=Origin of the vertebrate body plan via mechanically biased conservation of regular geometrical patterns in the structure of the blastula |journal=[[Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology]] |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0079610716300542|doi=10.1016/j.pbiomolbio.2016.06.007}} *{{cite journal |last=Pivar |first=S. |year=2011 |title=The origin of the vertebrate skeleton |journal=[[International Journal of Astrobiology]] |volume=10 |pages=45–65 |doi=10.1017/s147355041000025x }} *{{cite book |last=Pivar |first=S. |year=2009 |title=On the Origin of Form |publisher=[[North Atlantic Books]] |isbn= }} *{{cite book |last=Pivar |first=S. |year=2004 |title=Lifecode |publisher=Ryland Press |isbn= }} *{{cite book |last=Pivar |first=S. |year=1974 |title=The Barye Bronzes |publisher=[[Antique Collectors' Club]] |isbn= }}
